description: SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including the skin, joints, kidneys, and brain. Symptoms can vary depending on the person and over time.

description: MCTD is a rare autoimmune disease that shares features with SLE, polymyositis/dermatomyositis, and scleroderma. Symptoms can vary depending on the person and overlap with other autoimmune diseases.

description: Scleroderma is a chronic autoimmune disease that affects the skin and connective tissues. There are two main types: localized and systemic. Symptoms vary depending on the type and severity.
description: Polymyositis and dermatomyositis are rare autoimmune diseases that cause muscle weakness and skin inflammation. Symptoms and severity can vary between the two conditions.
description: RA is a chronic inflammatory autoimmune disease that primarily affects the joints. It can cause pain, stiffness, swelling, and joint damage. Symptoms can vary in severity and location.

description: PsA is an inflammatory arthritis that affects people with psoriasis, a skin condition. Symptoms include joint pain, stiffness, swelling, and skin changes. It can vary in severity and location.

description: Reactive arthritis is a type of inflammatory arthritis triggered by an infection elsewhere in the body, often the intestines or urinary tract. Symptoms include joint pain, swelling, and redness. It often affects the lower limbs.

description: Infectious arthritis is caused by an infection in the joint, usually bacterial or viral. Symptoms include joint pain, swelling, redness, and fever. It can affect any joint but commonly affects the knees, hips, and ankles.

description: Gout is a type of inflammatory arthritis caused by the buildup of uric acid crystals in the joints. It causes sudden, intense pain, swelling, and redness, usually in the big toe. It can also affect other joints.

description: Fibromyalgia is a chronic pain disorder causing widespread musculoskeletal pain along with fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. While not classified as an inflammatory arthritis, muscle inflammation is a contributing factor.
